The Court distinguished the situation before it from those where the employer was a private corporation separate from the band council (
Four B
), or, where a particular operation of an employer does not form an integral part of the main operation of that employer (
Empress Hotel
). It found that in enforcing provincial laws on the reserve, the band council was carrying out one of a number of powers entrusted to it by section 81 of the
Indian Act
, the regulating of traffic and the observance of law and order, which was an integral part of the normal operations assigned to the band: [20] The only operations or activities that a band council is empowered to carry on are those authorized by Parliament under the
Indian Act
, and in particular by s. 81:
